commentBody:
@NobodyTwo 

That makes two (and probably many more) of us - last August there was a double rebus puzzle I could not figure out for the life of me, even after reading the column. And only yesterday I encountered a similar stumper in the 2022 archive. It feels rotten to not understand the trick.

Today was very easy though - perhaps too easy? I got the trick very quickly, and actually the rebus helped me deal with the revealer, not the other way round. I had to look up some stuff though, as is often the case with American trivia, especially from many decades ago.

@NobodyTwo 

Congratulations!

Once you get used to the idea that there might be a rebus when an answer you’re sure of doesn’t fit, these puzzles get less frustrating and more fun.

@Dorothy 
It was obviously a self-deprecating joke. 





Emus have a sense of humor, no?

@Heidi
Keep COATI on file.  You'll see it again.

And it's a fun Wordle starter word.

@heironymous 

You make me wonder:  do our clocks mostly show just HOUR and MINUTE, while watches are more likely to show SECONDs?  
And now, in the age of digital everything, does it matter?

@Connor 

“Two plus two equals four.” 

“Two and two are four.”

@Man and 2 dogs 

The clue DID say 'poetic.'  
And if you don't know the COaTImundi, you're missing out!

@Mean Old Lady I did not know coatimundi! But now I do, and they’re cute little beasts.

On ETERNE, the “poetic” modifier did have me looking for something with that general vibe…but having never seen that word in my life (at least that I can recall, being decidedly unpoetic and no  particular fan of the medium in general), there was a limit to how much that could help me.

With different crosses, I’m sure I could have settled on ETERNE quickly enough…but between being utterly clueless on COATI, unsure about the R in IRA, and just the slightest bit tempted to reconsider ARE (if only because “equal” felt so weak/forced compared to most of the puzzle’s clueing), I found myself properly stumped.

@Man and 2 dogs 

Well, I got properly stumped elsewhere, so it shows that we all have our weak spots!

I'm considering a different moniker:  Woman and 1 Cat...but it doesn't have that zing....

@Vaer 

Thanks. I didn’t see that. 

I was never a fan of Vertex. It’s difficult to play on a tablet, and many of the drawings just didn’t interest me. There were a few (the bear trap in particular) that made me wonder who thought that was an appropriate image for this game?

@Vaer 
Addendum
The opening page to Vertex has been corrected to read that the last day will be August 29 not today.

@Barbara Rauch 

How is it lazy to create a clever puzzle that uses "hand" in so many ways and fit them all together? That takes work and effort. 

Also "do better" is totally obnoxious.

@sunny617 

What do you say when a beautiful coati passes by you?

"Sic transit gloria mundi!"

@Thomas 

I can hardly believe that you think scads is not a solid word, meaning a whole lot. I heard it growing up in the Midwest, I heard it in Texas, I hear it in California. You have been shortchanged in life if you were never given this word. No doubt you have scads of others (see list below to spot yours), but you would have used scads scads of times.

<a href="https://www.merriam-webster.com/thesaurus/scads" target="_blank">https://www.merriam-webster.com/thesaurus/scads</a>

@Eva H. 

“How was your band’s gig?”

“A lot of people came.” = “A lot of people turned out.”

@MoriokaBo According to the fandom, they are all indeed human. Leia refers to Alderaan's residents as "human beings", and in some canonized fan literature there are explanations of the spread of "human" colonists throughout the Republic.

So, yes, the humanoids are all apparently human, and the droids who capture C3PO are the first genuine aliens to appear on-screen, followed by the Sand People (now known as Tusken Raiders) and then the cornucopia at the Mos Eisley cantina.

And yes, I am a little ashamed to know this...
